Echinococcus: Sweden, wild fox, OIE
-----------------------------------
Information received on 16 Feb 2011 from Mr Leif Denneberg, CVO,
Director and Head of Department, Department for Animal Production and
Health, Swedish Board of Agriculture, Jonkoping, Sweden

Summary
-------
Report type: Immediate notification
Start date: 20 Dec 2010
Date of 1st confirmation of the event: 11 Feb 2011
Report date: 16 Feb 2011
Date submitted to OIE: 16 Feb 2011
Reason for notification: Reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 2004
Manifestation of disease: Sub-clinical infection
Causal agent: _Echinococcus multilocularis_
Nature of diagnosis: Laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country

New outbreaks
Outbreak 1: Lannerod, Lannerod, Uddevalla, Vastra Gotalands lan
Date of start of the outbreak: 20 Dec 2010
Outbreak status: Continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: Not applicable
Affected animals
Species: Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Wild species: - / 1 / 0 / 1 / 0
Affected Population: The affected animal was a wild fox (_Vulpes
vulpes_) shot during hunting in December 2010.
Summary of outbreaks: Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak statistics
Species: Apparent morbidity rate / Apparent mortality rate / Apparent
case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Wild species: ** / ** / 0.00 percent / **

* Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction
and/or slaughter
** Not calculated because of missing information

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection
Unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comments
This is the 1st occurrence of _Echinococcus multilocularis_ in Sweden.
Previous findings were related to _E. granulosus_. 300 foxes have been
analyzed within a routine surveillance during 2010. 54 of them came
from the County of Vastra Gotaland. Only one fox was found positive. A
plan with a more extensive surveillance will be set up. For human
health reasons treatment with praziquantel or epsiprantel is
recommended for dogs and cats at risk of exposure in the area where
the fox was found. In addition to the test noted below a SCT
(sedimentation and counting technique) test has been performed with
positive result.

Control measures
Measures applied
* Control of wildlife reservoirs
* Screening
* No vaccination
* No treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied
* No other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type: National Veterinary Institute (National laboratory)
Tests and results
Species: Test / Test date / Result
Wild species: real-time PCR / 11 Feb 2011 / Positive

Future Reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

Map of outbreak locations
Location of current outbreaks [see OIE site for map]

