Communicated by:
ProMED-Mail Corr.SB (Healthmap alert)*

[This is the 1st occurrence of _Echinococcus multilocularis_ in
Sweden; previous findings were related to _E. granulosus_. From a
routine surveillance of 300 foxes in Sweden, one fox out of 54
surveyed from Vastra Gotaland county was found positive with _E.
multilocularis_. Previous reports of _E. multilocularis_ in this
region was from the Svalbard islands of Norway in 2000, but no
incidents had been reported from the mainland of Norway or Sweden.

_Echinococcus multilocularis_ is a tapeworm that causes alveolar
echinococcosis in humans, also known as hydatidosis or hydatid
disease. The adult cestode resides in the small intestine of the
definitive hosts (mainly foxes, and to a lesser extent dogs, cats,
coyotes and wolves). The eggs are then passed into feces and ingested
by small rodents which act as an intermediate host. The eggs will then
hatch and penetrate the intestinal wall and migrate to the liver. In
humans, the cestode will remain indefinitely in the proliferative
stage, resulting in the invasion of surrounding liver tissues. But in
foxes, dogs and cats, the infection will be asymptomatic.

A diagram of the life cycle of echinococcosis can be found at:
<http://www.dpd.cdc.gov/dpdx/html/Echinococcosis.htm>

Once infected, humans take 10 to 20 years to develop symptoms, but
there is no effective treatment for the disease other than surgery to
remove the infected area or organ. Infection can be fatal if its
discovery is delayed.

Pet owners can accidentally become infected with _E. multilocularis_
from petting their pets and accidentally transferring eggs from hand
to mouth. The recommended course of action is to regularly give the
antihelminth medication praziquantel or epsiprantel to pet dogs and
cats in areas of risk to exposure. This would seem to be the safest
and most cost effective prevention method for echinococcosis.

Further information about echinococcosis can be found at the OIE website:
<http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.01.04_ECHINOCOCCOSIS.pdf>
- Mod.KL

The dwarf fox tape worm, _Echinococcus multilocularis_, the
aetiological agent of human alveolar echinococcosis, has been detected
in Sweden for the first time. The parasite was detected in a juvenile
vixen (_Vulpes vulpes_) during routine surveillance initiated in 2000.
During 2010 a total of 300 foxes were shot and investigated for EM,
either by the Sedimentation and counting technique (SCT) or egg
flotation and PCR; 1 fox was positive. The positive fox was shot in
December 2010 in the southwestern part of Sweden (Vastra Gotaland) and
was examined in February 2011. A total of 54 foxes originating from
this area were examined.

Between 2000 and 2009 a total of 2962 foxes and 49 raccoon dogs
(_Nyctereutes procyonoides_) have been examined for EM and all were
negative. Most foxes (n=2675) were examined with Coproantigen ELISA
and SCT and the raccoon dogs and the remaining foxes were examined
with SCT alone.

Intensified surveillance will be initiated to clarify the geographical
distribution of the parasite. - Mod.EP

Referring to the OIE map in the source URL, it can be seen that the
positive fox was found in a part of Sweden close to Denmark, which is
endemic for _E. multilocularis_. The 2 countries have been linked
across the Sound by a bridge-tunnel since 2002. It is probable that
an infected rodent, or even fox, made the crossing as a stowaway on a
cargo truck. - Mod.JW.
